Georges Niang was a unanimous first-team all-conference selection, and Deonte Burton is the preseason newcomer of the year in voting by the league’s coaches.
Jameel McKay and Monte Morris received honorable mention recognition. Oklahoma’s Buddy Hield is preseason player of the year.

He’s the only active player with 1,500 points, 450 rebounds and 300 assists.
Burton, a transfer from Marquette, will be eligible Dec. 19 to face Northern Iowa in the Big Four Classic at Wells Fargo Arena.
Morris, a junior, was a second-team all-Big 12 pick last season after averaging 11.9 points and leading the league with 5.2 assists. He was No. 1 nationally with a 4.6 assist-to-turnover ratio.
“Monte is a winner,” coach Steve Prohm said. “Those kids from Flint (Mich.) are tough.”
Despite not being eligible until mid-December, McKay was a Big 12 third-team pick last season and the league’s top defensive player after averaging 7.6 rebounds and 2.4 blocks a game.
DES MOINES REGISTER
Peterson: Expectations are crazy for ISU hoops — or are they?
With all this talent, are there enough touches to keep everyone happy?
“It’s about winning,” said Prohm, whose Murray State team had a 29-6 record last season. “The more we win, the more opportunities all of us will have as players.
“If you saw my team last year in November, everybody shot it, everybody was trying to score, and we were terrible.
“Once they understood about making the extra pass, playing together and playing the right way, great things started to happen.
“They understand the more success we have as a team.”
Iowa State opens the season with a Nov. 6 exhibition against Grand Valley State. The first official game is Nov. 13 against Colorado in Sioux Falls, S.D.
Preseason Player of the Year: Buddy Hield, Oklahoma
Preseason Newcomer of the Year: Deonte Burton, Iowa State
